\description{
\code{BasicCommand} is the root \link[R6:R6Class]{R6} class for all TNT command
objects in \pkg{nitro}. It establishes the core interface that every
command must support: a name, a description, dependency management,
rendering, and queue integration.

This class is not exported. It is intended to be subclassed by
\link{StandardCommand} or other intermediate classes.
}
\details{
\subsection{Subclassing}{

Subclasses should call \code{super$initialize(name, description)} in their
own \code{initialize()} method. The \verb{$name} and \verb{$description} fields become
read-only after the first assignment. All other fields, including
\verb{$provides}, can be reassigned freely after construction.

The following methods are designed to be overridden:
\itemize{
\item \strong{\verb{$render()}} — must return a character string containing the
formatted TNT command. The base implementation returns invisibly.
\item \strong{\verb{$format()}} — should return a human-readable summary of the
command's current configuration. The base implementation returns
invisibly.
\item \strong{\verb{$enqueue(.queue)}} — should add the command (and any follow-up
commands) to a \link{CommandQueue}. The base implementation creates or
passes through a queue without adding anything.
}
}

\subsection{Dependency system}{

Commands can declare named dependencies via \verb{$new_dependency()}. Each
dependency has:
\itemize{
\item A \code{name} — used as the key in the \verb{$dependencies} list.
\item A \code{required} flag — determines whether the dependency appears in
\verb{$requires} (\code{TRUE}) or \verb{$optional} (\code{FALSE}).
\item A \code{callback} function — applied to the value when the dependency is
set via \verb{$set_dependency()}, allowing validation or transformation.
}
}

\subsection{Inline commands}{

Commands with \verb{$inline} set to \code{TRUE} are not written directly into the
TNT script during execution. Instead, their rendered output is written
to a separate temporary file and a \verb{proc <filename>;} call is
substituted in the script at that position. This is intended for
commands such as \link{ReadTreesCommand} that may produce very long output,
and keeps the main script readable.
}
}
